@article{Bronnikov&Koch2023,
  science={Economics},
  abstract={Loneliness is a significant issue of our times: 
            every second individual feels lonely at least occasionally, 
            and every seventeenth person experiences it often or always. 
            The literature highlights the profound negative impact 
            of loneliness on both mental and physical health. 
            However, loneliness remains an area that is not thoroughly researched. 
            Specifically, there is a lack of studies on social 
            and economic preferences that establish the causal effect of loneliness. 
            To the best of our knowledge, our paper is the first 
            to address this using economic laboratory settings. 
            We document the multidimensional effects of loneliness 
            on social and economic preferences. 
            The key implication of our study is that it elucidates why and 
            by which mechanisms lonely individuals are more 
            susceptible to exploitation compared to those who are not (or less) lonely, 
            putting them at a higher risk. 
